        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe a mosaic of two pointings centered on the cores of the two interacting galaxies. Two overlapping basebands of the Band 3 receiver will be centered at the red-shifted frequencies of the CO 1-0 (rest frequency 115.271 GHz) and CN J=3/2-1/2 ( rest frequency 113.49 GHz). The low excitation temperature and critical density of the CO 1-0 transition makes it optimal to trace diffuse gas in the outflow and in the region between the two galaxies. Also, Band 3 provides a large field of view (55"), which minimizes the number of pointings required to map the galaxy pair. The CN transition is a good tracer of  photo-dissociation regions (Meier &amp; Turner 2005) and will pinpoint sites of star formation. 

Given the high declination of our target, we have performed a simulation with the ALMA online OST in order to confirm the feasibility of the proposed observations. As a model we used opacity-corrected NII data, which resemble the CO distribution mapped by Yun &amp; Hibbard 2001. Figure 2 shows that after an on-source time of 30 minutes in  C34-2 configuration (304 m baseline) we will be able to recover most of the emission. After a total observing time of less than 2.5 hours we will reach a sensitivity of 0.5 mJy/beam in a 3" beam (1.5 kpc) and 50 km/s resolution, which is 20 times better than in Yun &amp; Hibbard 2001. 
Previous observations of molecular outflows (Cicone et al., 2013) show that these have extents of 2-10 kpc and flux densities of a few mJy in a similar beam. Our setup should be able to detect any outflowing molecular gas at least at the 5-sigma level. 
</prj:justificationText>
