    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The Mice, one of the most famous members of the original Toomre merger sequence, comprise two very massive gas rich galaxies caught in a very early stage of merging, about 170Myr after first passage. New optical integral field spectroscopic (IFS) data from the CALIFA survey, combined with archival multi-wavelength observations, reveals that the close encounter has had an enormous impact on the ionised gas and kinematics of both galaxies, but has not (yet) triggered any globally significant star formation. Both galaxies have bicones of ionised gas extending to 10-15'' in radius (~4.4-6.6kpc); in NGC4676A the bicones can only explained by fast shocks driven by a massive outflow. ALMA can map the whole system (50''x80'') in CO(1-0) and CN, at 3" resolution in 2.5 hours. The unique combination of CALIFA+ALMA will reveal the extent to which star formation is both fueled and extinguished by the gravitational forces of a close encounter. Scientific and public interest in merging galaxies, combined with the complementarity to previous ALMA observations of the Antennae, and our team's work with CALIFA and numerical simulations, will provide a unique dataset and ensure a wide impact.</prp:abstract>
